One approach to find the shortest palindrome for a given string is to iterate over the string and check if the current substring is a palindrome. If it is not a palindrome, then we can add characters to the end of the substring until it becomes a palindrome. We can repeat this process for all substrings of the given string and return the shortest palindrome found.
Here is the C++ code to implement this approach:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;
bool is_palindrome(string s) {
    int n = s.length();
    for (int i = 0; i < n / 2; i++) {
        if (s[i] != s[n - i - 1]) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}
string shortest_palindrome(string s) {
    int n = s.length();
    string shortest = s;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (int j = i + 1; j <= n; j++) {
            string substring = s.substr(i, j - i);
            if (!is_palindrome(substring)) {
                string rev_substring = substring;
                reverse(rev_substring.begin(), rev_substring.end());
                string palindrome = substring + rev_substring;
                if (palindrome.length() < shortest.length()) {
                    shortest = palindrome;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return shortest;
}
int main() {
    string s = "hello";
    string shortest = shortest_palindrome(s);
    cout << shortest << endl; // Output: helloleh
    return 0;
}
```
In this code, the `is_palindrome` function checks if a given string is a palindrome or not. The `shortest_palindrome` function iterates over all substrings of the given string and checks if they are palindromes. If a substring is not a palindrome, it adds the reverse of the substring to the end of it to make it a palindrome. Finally, it returns the shortest palindrome found.

