To store and encrypt data using JSON format, you can use the CommonCrypto library in Swift. Here's an example of how to encrypt and decrypt JSON data using the CommonCrypto library:
```swift
import CommonCrypto
// Define the data to be encrypted
let jsonData = try! JSONSerialization.data(withJSONObject: ["creditCardNumber": "1234567890123456", "expirationDate": "12/25"], options: [])
// Define the encryption key
let key = "myEncryptionKey".data(using: .utf8)!
// Define the initialization vector (IV)
let iv = "myInitializationVector".data(using: .utf8)!
// Define the output buffer
var encryptedData = Data(count: jsonData.count + kCCBlockSizeAES128)
// Perform the encryption
let status = key.withUnsafeBytes { keyBytes in
    iv.withUnsafeBytes { ivBytes in
        jsonData.withUnsafeBytes { dataBytes in
            CCCrypt(CCOperation(kCCEncrypt),
                    CCAlgorithm(kCCAlgorithmAES),
                    CCOptions(kCCOptionPKCS7Padding),
                    keyBytes, key.count,
                    ivBytes,
                    dataBytes, jsonData.count,
                    &encryptedData, encryptedData.count,
                    nil)
        }
    }
}
// Check the encryption status
guard status == kCCSuccess else {
    print("Encryption failed with error code \(status)")
    return
}
// Print the encrypted data
print("Encrypted data: \(encryptedData.base64EncodedString())")
// Define the output buffer for decryption
var decryptedData = Data(count: encryptedData.count)
// Perform the decryption
let decryptionStatus = key.withUnsafeBytes { keyBytes in
    iv.withUnsafeBytes { ivBytes in
        encryptedData.withUnsafeBytes { dataBytes in
            CCCrypt(CCOperation(kCCDecrypt),
                    CCAlgorithm(kCCAlgorithmAES),
                    CCOptions(kCCOptionPKCS7Padding),
                    keyBytes, key.count,
                    ivBytes,
                    dataBytes, encryptedData.count,
                    &decryptedData, decryptedData.count,
                    nil)
        }
    }
}
// Check the decryption status
guard decryptionStatus == kCCSuccess else {
    print("Decryption failed with error code \(decryptionStatus)")
    return
}
// Convert the decrypted data to a JSON object
let decryptedJson = try! JSONSerialization.jsonObject(with: decryptedData, options: [])
// Print the decrypted JSON object
print("Decrypted JSON: \(decryptedJson)")
```
In this example, we first define the data to be encrypted as a JSON object. We then define the encryption key and initialization vector (IV) as data objects. We create an output buffer for the encrypted data and use the CCCrypt function to perform the encryption. We then print the encrypted data and create an output buffer for the decrypted data. We use the CCCrypt function again to perform the decryption and convert the decrypted data to a JSON object. Finally, we print the decrypted JSON object.

