```
public class BinarySearchTree {

    private Node root;

    private class Node {
        int key;
        Node left, right;

        public Node(int item) {
            key = item;
            left = right = null;
        }
    }

    public BinarySearchTree() {
        root = null;
    }

    public void insert(int key) {
        root = insertRec(root, key);
    }

    private Node insertRec(Node root, int key) {
        if (root == null) {
            root = new Node(key);
            return root;
        }

        if (key < root.key)
            root.left = insertRec(root.left, key);
        else if (key > root.key)
            root.right = insertRec(root.right, key);

        return root;
    }

    public void inorder() {
        inorderRec(root);
    }

    private void inorderRec(Node root) {
        if (root != null) {
            inorderRec(root.left);
            System.out.print(root.key + " ");
            inorderRec(root.right);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BinarySearchTree bst = new BinarySearchTree();
        bst.insert(50);
        bst.insert(30);
        bst.insert(20);
        bst.insert(40);
        bst.insert(70);
        bst.insert(60);
        bst.insert(80);

        System.out.println("Inorder traversal of the binary search tree:");
        bst.inorder();
    }
}
```
In this code, we create a `Node` class to represent each node in the binary search tree. Each `Node` has a `key` value, and `left` and `right` pointers to its left and right child nodes.
The `BinarySearchTree` class has a `root` variable to store the root node of the tree. It also has methods to insert a new node into the tree (`insert`), traverse the tree in order (`inorder`), and a `main` method to test the implementation.
The `insert` method uses a recursive `insertRec` method to find the correct position to insert the new node based on its key value. The `inorder` method uses a recursive `inorderRec` method to traverse the tree in order and print out the node values.
When we run the `main` method, it will create a binary search tree with the values {50, 30, 20, 40, 70, 60, 80}, and then print out the inorder traversal of the tree: "20 30 40 50 60 70 80".

