To efficiently find the second smallest and second largest values in an integer array named arr with n elements, we can use the divide and conquer method. The basic idea is to divide the array into two parts, find the minimum and maximum values in each part, and then compare them to get the second smallest and second largest values.
The time complexity of the divide and conquer method is O(n), where n is the size of the array. As we increase the size of the array, the time complexity will also increase linearly.
To speed up the recursive computations of the minimum, maximum, second smallest, and second largest values in each part of the divided array, we can use parallel processing. We can divide the array into multiple sub-arrays and process each sub-array in parallel using multiple threads. This will reduce the overall computation time and improve the performance of the algorithm.
Here is the Java code implementation that utilizes parallel processing to find the second smallest and second largest values in an integer array:
```java
import java.util.concurrent.*;
public class SecondMinMax {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 12, 7, 3, 9, 1, 6, 4};
        int n = arr.length;
        // parallel processing
        ForkJoinPool pool = new ForkJoinPool();
        ParallelMinMax task = new ParallelMinMax(arr, 0, n-1);
        int[] results = pool.invoke(task);
        // output results
        System.out.println("Second smallest: " + results[0]);
        System.out.println("Second largest: " + results[1]);
    }
    // parallel recursive task
    static class ParallelMinMax extends RecursiveTask<int[]> {
        private int[] arr;
        private int lo, hi;
        public ParallelMinMax(int[] arr, int lo, int hi) {
            this.arr = arr;
            this.lo = lo;
            this.hi = hi;
        }
        @Override
        protected int[] compute() {
            if (hi - lo <= 1) {
                int min = Math.min(arr[lo], arr[hi]);
                int max = Math.max(arr[lo], arr[hi]);
                return new int[]{min, max};
            } else {
                int mid = (lo + hi) / 2;
                ParallelMinMax left = new ParallelMinMax(arr, lo, mid);
                ParallelMinMax right = new ParallelMinMax(arr, mid+1, hi);
                left.fork();
                int[] rightResult = right.compute();
                int[] leftResult = left.join();
                // merge results
                int[] results = new int[4];
                results[0] = (leftResult[0] < rightResult[0]) ? leftResult[0] : rightResult[0];
                results[1] = (leftResult[1] > rightResult[1]) ? leftResult[1] : rightResult[1];
                results[2] = (leftResult[0] > rightResult[0] && leftResult[0] < rightResult[1]) ? leftResult[0] : rightResult[0];
                results[3] = (leftResult[1] < rightResult[1] && leftResult[1] > rightResult[0]) ? leftResult[1] : rightResult[1];
                return results;
            }
        }
    }
}
```
The code uses the ForkJoinPool class to create a thread pool and the RecursiveTask class to implement the parallel recursive task. The task divides the array into two parts, creates two sub-tasks for each part, and merges the results to get the second smallest and second largest values.
To modify the algorithm to handle duplicates in the array and return the indices of the second smallest and second largest values, we can use a TreeMap to store the values and their indices. Here is the modified Java code implementation:
```java
import java.util.*;
public class SecondMinMax {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 12, 7, 3, 9, 1, 6, 4};
        int n = arr.length;
        // find second smallest and second largest with indices
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new TreeMap<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            map.put(arr[i], i);
        }
        int i = 0;
        int secondSmallest = 0;
        int secondLargest = 0;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
            if (i == 1) {
                secondSmallest = entry.getKey();
            } else if (i == n-2) {
                secondLargest = entry.getKey();
            }
            i++;
        }
        int secondSmallestIndex = map.get(secondSmallest);
        int secondLargestIndex = map.get(secondLargest);
        // output results
        System.out.println("Second smallest: " + secondSmallest + " at index " + secondSmallestIndex);
        System.out.println("Second largest: " + secondLargest + " at index " + secondLargestIndex);
    }
}
```
The code uses a TreeMap to store the values and their indices, and then finds the second smallest and second largest values with their indices by iterating through the map.

