Certainly! Here's an implementation of the Merge Sort algorithm in Java that sorts a list of integers in ascending order with a time complexity of O(n log n) or better:
```
public class MergeSort {
    public static void sort(int[] arr) {
        if (arr == null || arr.length <= 1) {
            return;
        }
        int[] temp = new int[arr.length];
        mergeSort(arr, temp, 0, arr.length - 1);
    }
    private static void mergeSort(int[] arr, int[] temp, int left, int right) {
        if (left >= right) {
            return;
        }
        int mid = (left + right) / 2;
        mergeSort(arr, temp, left, mid);
        mergeSort(arr, temp, mid + 1, right);
        merge(arr, temp, left, mid, right);
    }
    private static void merge(int[] arr, int[] temp, int left, int mid, int right) {
        for (int i = left; i <= right; i++) {
            temp[i] = arr[i];
        }
        int i = left;
        int j = mid + 1;
        int k = left;
        while (i <= mid && j <= right) {
            if (temp[i] <= temp[j]) {
                arr[k++] = temp[i++];
            } else {
                arr[k++] = temp[j++];
            }
        }
        while (i <= mid) {
            arr[k++] = temp[i++];
        }
    }
}
```
To use this code to sort a list of integers in ascending order, you can simply call the `sort` method and pass in the array as a parameter:
```
int[] arr = {5, 3, 8, 4, 2};
MergeSort.sort(arr);
System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr)); // prints [2, 3, 4, 5, 8]
```
This implementation of Merge Sort uses a divide-and-conquer approach to recursively split the array into smaller subarrays, sort each subarray, and then merge the sorted subarrays back together. The `merge` method is used to merge two sorted subarrays together into a single sorted array. The `temp` array is used to store the original array while it is being sorted.

