Yes, a pre-trained natural language processing model can be utilized to improve the accuracy of sentiment analysis or question answering tasks, while minimizing the amount of required data. One way to do this is through transfer learning, where a pre-trained language model is fine-tuned on a smaller dataset specific to the task at hand.
Here's an example of how this can be implemented in C++ code using the Hugging Face Transformers library:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <torch/torch.h>
#include <transformers/convert_utils.h>
#include <transformers/modeling_bert.h>
#include <transformers/modeling_gpt2.h>
#include <transformers/tokenization_bert.h>
#include <transformers/tokenization_gpt2.h>
using namespace transformers;
int main() {
    // Load pre-trained GPT-3 model
    std::string model_path = "path/to/gpt3/model";
    auto config = GPT2Config::from_pretrained(model_path);
    auto model = GPT2Model::from_pretrained(model_path, config);
    // Fine-tune on question answering task
    std::string qa_dataset_path = "path/to/qa/dataset";
    auto tokenizer = GPT2Tokenizer::from_pretrained(model_path);
    auto qa_dataset = load_qa_dataset(qa_dataset_path);
    auto qa_model = GPT2ForQuestionAnswering(config);
    auto optimizer = torch::optim::Adam(qa_model->parameters(), 5e-5);
    fine_tune_qa(qa_model, tokenizer, qa_dataset, optimizer);
    // Use fine-tuned model for question answering
    std::string question = "What is the capital of France?";
    std::string context = "France is a country in Western Europe.";
    auto inputs = tokenizer.encode_plus(question, context, Tokenizer::pad_token, Tokenizer::pad_token_id, true);
    auto input_ids = torch::tensor(inputs.input_ids).unsqueeze(0);
    auto attention_mask = torch::tensor(inputs.attention_mask).unsqueeze(0);
    auto start_logits = qa_model->forward(input_ids, attention_mask).start_logits;
    auto end_logits = qa_model->forward(input_ids, attention_mask).end_logits;
    auto start_index = start_logits.argmax().item<int64_t>();
    auto end_index = end_logits.argmax().item<int64_t>();
    auto answer = tokenizer.decode(inputs.ids(start_index, end_index+1));
    std::cout << "Question: " << question << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Context: " << context << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Answer: " << answer << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
In this example, we first load a pre-trained GPT-3 model using the `GPT2Model` class from the Hugging Face Transformers library. We then fine-tune the model on a question answering dataset using the `GPT2ForQuestionAnswering` class and the `fine_tune_qa` function provided by the library. Finally, we use the fine-tuned model to answer a sample question by encoding the question and context using the `GPT2Tokenizer`, passing the inputs through the model, and decoding the output using the same tokenizer.
Note that this is just a basic example and there are many ways to fine-tune a pre-trained language model and use it for different tasks. The Hugging Face Transformers library provides a wide range of pre-trained models and tools for fine-tuning and inference, making it a great resource for implementing natural language processing tasks in C++.

