To solve this problem using a hash table, we can count the frequency of each element in the array by storing it as a key in the hash table and its frequency as the value. Then, we can iterate through the hash table and find the two elements with a frequency of 1.
Here is the Java code implementation for this problem:
```
import java.util.*;
public class NonRepeatingElements {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {2, 3, 7, 9, 11, 2, 3, 11};
        Map<Integer, Integer> freqMap = new HashMap<>();

        // Count the frequency of each element in the array
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            if (freqMap.containsKey(arr[i])) {
                freqMap.put(arr[i], freqMap.get(arr[i]) + 1);
            } else {
                freqMap.put(arr[i], 1);
            }
        }

        // Find the two elements with a frequency of 1
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : freqMap.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() == 1) {
                result.add(entry.getKey());
            }
            if (result.size() == 2) {
                break;
            }
        }

        // Output the result
        System.out.println("The two non-repeating elements in the array are: " + result.get(0) + " and " + result.get(1));
    }
}
```
